{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_aetna_ver02/data/sn92051355/00393346723/1945081601/0725.xml":{"full_text":"AFL Directs P!eo to Congress\n_._.\u2014\u2014-\u2014\n\"By Common Consent\nBy EUGENE MITCHELL, Dept. 334\n99\nA paragraph in the \"Declaration\nof Purposes\" of the National\nGrange contains food for thought.\nIt reads, \"We long to see the an\ntagonism between Capital and La\nbor removed by common consent\nand by enlightened statesmanship\nworthy of the Twentieth Century.\"\nHere, in a few well chosen words,\nwritten by some rural statesman, is\nthe key to the solution of one of\nAmerica's great permanent (so far)\nproblems, the antagonism between\nCapital and Labor.\nWhere will we find that \"en\nlightened statesmanship?\" There\nis only one worthwhile place to\nlook for it\u2014in our own councils.\nIf genuine and dynamic Labor\nManagement committees, dedicat\ning themselves to the goal of peace\nin industry by common consent\ncould start functioning in some\nimportant industry, their course\nwould be followed by the entire\ncountry. Most all of us are getting\npretty sick of industrial strife.\nOnly the Communists, the Labor\nhaters, and the rabble-rousers want\nmore of it, for obvious reasons.\nThey benefit by strikes, lockouts,\nand slow downs, etc. Trouble is\ntheir life-blood. If these birds are\never downed, they will go down\nfighting, we can be sure.\nThe document recently signed\nby William Green, Philip Murray,\nand Eric Johnston points out the\nway for us. Followed through, this\nCharter for Peace in Industry could\nwell become one of the great turn\ning points in the internal develop\nment of the U. S. An underlying\nprinciple is the proposition that\nCapitalism MUST be made to\nwork. Another important angle is\nthis; the politician is ignored.\nThese last twenty or more years\nhave seen a steady increase in gov\nernment, in public ownership, and\nin bureaucracy, until a huge pro\nportion of our people are engaged\nin regulating the affairs of the rest\nof us, and a fourth or more of the\nNational income goes into taxes to i\npay the ordinary costs of govern\nment, state and local, as well as\nnational. This is a definite trend\ntoward State Socialism, and must\nbe stopped and turned back to the\npoint where it is sensible. Peace\nin industry would start the ball\nrolling, as much of this dangerous\nincrease has been brought on by\nindustrial strife; witness the last\ntwelve years.\nThis burying of the hatchet need\nnot be a one-sided proposition at\nall. Both sides would benefit by\nit, to say nothing of the public at\nlarge. Just the relief from the\nconstant negotiating and squab\nbling would make it worth while.\nThe usual bone of contention in ne\ngotiations between management\nand labor is wages and hours. Let's\nlook at this for a minute.\nAmerica's brand of Capitalism\nrests on the idea that well paid\nworking people, with leisure time,\nare the purchasers of nearly all the\nproducts of America's industry. A\npoor family does not buy a new\ncar or radio or house. They simply\ncannot do it. But with a decent\nincome and the leisure to enjoy\nsuch things, nine out of ten people\nwill buy, and have the money to\npay, too. Income lost from\nstrikes does not buy anything.\nBusiness lost by the closing of an\nindustrial plant only goes else\nwhere, often permanently. Tur\nhioil not reaching the strike or\nlockout stage results in a poor\nproduct, spotty delivery and an\nominous Increase in the influence\nof the extremists on both sides, to\nsay nothing of the probable crea\ntion of another bureau. The shab\nbiness of certain makes of cars\nbuilt during the sit-down strike\nperiod in the Detroit area several\nyears ago, illustrates one of the\nevil results of such warfare. In\ncidentally, the role played by the\npolitician in that struggle is well\nremembered, but not with rever\nence.\nIf the will to find and keep the\npeace is present on both sides the\npeace can be written and won. Af\nter all, in any given business, the\nemployer and the employee are\nreally partners. Neither can get\nalong without the other under any\nstretch of the imagination. An\nexperienced, satisfied and ambi\ntious team of workers is an inval\nuable asset to any concern. A side\nlight on this is the fact that people\nwho are proud of the concern they\nare part of are always great \"push\ners\" of the firm's product; unoffi\ncial salesmen, in other words. Many\nprogressive concerns have realized\nhow valuable the asset of good\nwill in their own house is, end\nhave prospered.\nAn article in a recent Readers\nDigest about the Lincoln Electric\nCo., of Cleveland, makers of weld- I\ning machines, describes the fine\nresult obtainable when Manage\nment and Labor meet each other\nhalf way. Employees have high in\ncomes and the concern has forged\nahead of all competition by hav\ning an excellent product at a low\ner price. The present writer has\nnot been out to Cleveland, but will\ntake the magazine's word for it,\nrather than the word of some agi\ntator or labor-hater. These peo-\npie can cook up facts and figures\nto disprove anything anywhere, and\nwe ordinary folks simply cannot go\nout to see such examples for our\nselves.\nYes, peace in industry pays.\nThe enemies of the peace are not\nnumerous, but they are powerful\nand unscrupulous, and well en\ntrenched in both sides of the house.\nLet's look them over.\nAnyone who works with an av\nerage bunch of people gets to know\ncertain things about them. He\nsees that probably ninety per cent\nof them are on the job to improve\ntheir lot in life, increase their use\nfulness to their concern and to so\nciety, and to enjoy some of the fine\nthings the Twentieth Century has\nbrought forth. And they want to\nsee an end to wars, both internal\nand external. But the other ten\nper cent? We all know them.\nGrafters, lazybones, dissipaters,\nand life-long soreheads. The dan\ngerous ones, though, are those who\nseek, like scum, to rise to the top\nin the so-called class war they so\neagerly promote.\nOn the Management side of the\nhouse, there are some disagreeable\ncharacters, too, probably about in\nthe same proportion. Some of the\nsmaller-minded just despise work\ning people and their aspirations,\nhaving the ancient feudal mental\nity of \"Master and Slave.\" Some\nfear the progress labor has made\nthese past hundred years, seeing it\nas a threat to their own dominance.\nOthers want to keep wages low and\nhours long so as to pocket more of\nthe profits themselves.\nDo we, Capitol and Labor, NEED\nto be led around by these ugly mi\nnorities? Of course not! But we\noften are. Both can and must\nclean house. We must get rid of\nthe trouble makers.\nWe must also freeze out the pol-\nitician, whose interest is votes, in!\nExecutive CoMmctt CatM r or\nLegislation Deaiing W^ itit\nReconversion s Lfnman Side\nChicago\u2014The American Federation of Labor's Execu\ntive Council, supreme governing body of the Federation be\ntween annual conventions, issued a number of important\ndeclarations at its quarterly meeting here last week.\nOutstanding was an appeal addressed to Congress call\ning for prompt action this fall on a program dealing with\nthe \"human side\" of reconversion. Also, President Truman\nwas urged to send a special message to Congress when ses\nsions are resumed, asking for speed on the program.\nThis legislation, the Council said, should include: Higher\nunemployment compensation benefits; a 65-cent an hour min\nimum wage; a great post-war housing program; expansion\nof social security, and health insurance.\nAlso, the Councn announcea\nit would \"mobilize all forces\nof the A. F. of L.\" to defeat\nthe Ball-Hatch-Burton Anti\nLabor bill. The measure was\ndescribed as \"so thoroughly ob\njectionable\" as to be beyond\ncorrection by amendments.\nA housing bill introduced by Sen.\n\"Bob\" Wagner of New York, which\nwould provide for construction of\n1,200,000 housing units annually,\nwas singled out for special em\nphasis as \"the most important step\nto prompt attainment of foil em\nployment after the war.\"\nAlso, the Council pleaded for\nprompt scaling down of war pro\nduction to the needs of a one-front\nwar, so that reconversion to peace\ntime output may be speeded up be\nfore it becomes \"too late to avoid a\nmajor post-war depression.\n\"Our country is far less prepared\nfor peace than it was for war at\nthe time of Pearl Harbor,\" the\nCouncil warned.\nthe long run. The fact that both\nthe CIO and the AFofL list among\ntheir assets the power they have\nin Washington, the power of sev\neral million votes apiece, and the\npower of fate treasuries, is proof\nenough for this writer that the pol\nitician must be frozen out. The\nimpotence of Independent unions\nwhen it comes to getting grievances\nsettled in the District of Confusion\nspeaks for itself, too.\nHuman nature being what it is,\nsome governmental regulation will\nno doubt continue to be necessary.\nIf we must turn to government,\nlet it be to a state government,\nwhere we can soon \"throw the ras\ncals out\" if they start using our\ntroubles as a political football.\nThere is hardly a case of trouble\nbetween Management and Labor\nthat cannot be settled, to the bene\nfit of all, right in the Labor-Man\nagement Committee. If both part\nners would earnestly subscribe to\nand improve upon the rules Mated\nin the Green-Mur ray-Johnston\nagreement, and if they would paste\nup in their minds these words; \"We\ntoo, long to see the antagonism\nbetween Capital and Labor re\nmoved by common consent and by\nan enlightened statesmanship wor\nthy of the Twentieth Century,\"\nthen America could really lead the\nworld in the most happiness pet\ncapita as well as the highest stand\nard of living.\nLike charity, this should begin at\nhome, right here on the east\nbank of the Thames.\nKMP OM.\nW!TH WM BOMBS I\n\n\n\"Just a Guy in a Foxhole\"\n\u2014I know,\nI haven't got much say\u2014\nJust my living;\nAnd a G. 1. pay\u2014\nI ain't a general;\nBut I still can think\nAnd \"pop\" a Jap\nAs quick as I can wink\nAnd this\nIs how I'm thinking\nIn this hole:\nOnce this Is finished\nAnd we've won our goal,\nI wonder\nJust what kind of welcome\nI will get?\nFor somehow\nLying here I can't forget\u2014\nMy dad\nFought overseas in France,\nAnd helped\nTo kick the Jerries in the pants.\nHe got\nA big citation and his passage home\nAnd settled down there,\nNever more to roam,\nOr so he thought,\nUntil disgrace\nWas brought upon him, new peace\ntaugjht\nThat veterans\nWere not heroea, as wo thought!\nAH martial thoughts\nWere roon discouraged\nAnd his boys\nCave up their pop-guns\nAnd their military toys;\nWere taught\nThat only savages would tight\nThat dad, Our Hero,\nWas somehow, not right!\nDepression caught us\nAnd my dad, an A. E. F.\nMarched down to Washington\nWhere \"Polls\" were deaf\u2014\nTo honor and\nTo duty, and\nTo God.\nThought more of \"dough\"\nThan of the common elod!\nDon't sound so good\u2014and\nDoe? It now?\nI'm thinking\nWhat will happen\nAfter all this row?\nWill I go heme\nAnd marry, settle down\nAnd find\nThere alnt a }ob for me\nIn town?\nRepented by pepnlar r*ti\nWe'** fighting her#\nAnd boy!\ndo mean war!\nDo you Back There\nKnow what we re fighting fort\nFor home and babiea\nAnd a job of work!\nNo dole!\nNo guy want# that\nUnless he is a \"jerk\"!\u2014\nI know the home folks\nThink of us\nAnd write,\nI hate to tell you\nThat it ain't enough\u2014good night'\nBut there it is;\nJust plain horse sense\nAnd elear enough\nTo men who ain't just dense\nW*Te fighting Here!\nBut who\nIs fighting there?\nAnd what will we get,\nWhen we do come up for air?\nIt's up to you, our brothers.\nAll good Union men\nTo fight!\nAnd WIN! That war!\nBefore\nWe're heme again!\n\u2014Howland Bishe#","height":"20655","width":"13974"}}
